    1824                 :            : /* Walk the tree X, and record accesses to variables.  If X is written by the
    1825                 :            :    parent tree, WRITER is the parent.
    1826                 :            :    We store accesses in one of the two lists: PBEFORE_SP, and PNO_SP.  If this
    1827                 :            :    expression or its only operand forces a sequence point, then everything up
    1828                 :            :    to the sequence point is stored in PBEFORE_SP.  Everything else gets stored
    1829                 :            :    in PNO_SP.
    1830                 :            :    Once we return, we will have emitted warnings if any subexpression before
    1831                 :            :    such a sequence point could be undefined.  On a higher level, however, the
    1832                 :            :    sequence point may not be relevant, and we'll merge the two lists.
    1833                 :            : 
    1834                 :            :    Example: (b++, a) + b;
    1835                 :            :    The call that processes the COMPOUND_EXPR will store the increment of B
    1836                 :            :    in PBEFORE_SP, and the use of A in PNO_SP.  The higher-level call that
    1837                 :            :    processes the PLUS_EXPR will need to merge the two lists so that
    1838                 :            :    eventually, all accesses end up on the same list (and we'll warn about the
    1839                 :            :    unordered subexpressions b++ and b.
    1840                 :            : 
    1841                 :            :    A note on merging.  If we modify the former example so that our expression
    1842                 :            :    becomes
    1843                 :            :      (b++, b) + a
    1844                 :            :    care must be taken not simply to add all three expressions into the final
    1845                 :            :    PNO_SP list.  The function merge_tlist takes care of that by merging the
    1846                 :            :    before-SP list of the COMPOUND_EXPR into its after-SP list in a special
    1847                 :            :    way, so that no more than one access to B is recorded.  */

    7875                 :            : /* Setup a TYPE_DECL node as a typedef representation.
    7876                 :            : 
    7877                 :            :    X is a TYPE_DECL for a typedef statement.  Create a brand new
    7878                 :            :    ..._TYPE node (which will be just a variant of the existing
    7879                 :            :    ..._TYPE node with identical properties) and then install X
    7880                 :            :    as the TYPE_NAME of this brand new (duplicate) ..._TYPE node.
    7881                 :            : 
    7882                 :            :    The whole point here is to end up with a situation where each
    7883                 :            :    and every ..._TYPE node the compiler creates will be uniquely
    7884                 :            :    associated with AT MOST one node representing a typedef name.
    7885                 :            :    This way, even though the compiler substitutes corresponding
    7886                 :            :    ..._TYPE nodes for TYPE_DECL (i.e. "typedef name") nodes very
    7887                 :            :    early on, later parts of the compiler can always do the reverse
    7888                 :            :    translation and get back the corresponding typedef name.  For
    7889                 :            :    example, given:
    7890                 :            : 
    7891                 :            :         typedef struct S MY_TYPE;
    7892                 :            :         MY_TYPE object;
    7893                 :            : 
    7894                 :            :    Later parts of the compiler might only know that `object' was of
    7895                 :            :    type `struct S' if it were not for code just below.  With this
    7896                 :            :    code however, later parts of the compiler see something like:
    7897                 :            : 
    7898                 :            :         struct S' == struct S
    7899                 :            :         typedef struct S' MY_TYPE;
    7900                 :            :         struct S' object;
    7901                 :            : 
    7902                 :            :     And they can then deduce (from the node for type struct S') that
    7903                 :            :     the original object declaration was:
    7904                 :            : 
    7905                 :            :                 MY_TYPE object;
    7906                 :            : 
    7907                 :            :     Being able to do this is important for proper support of protoize,
    7908                 :            :     and also for generating precise symbolic debugging information
    7909                 :            :     which takes full account of the programmer's (typedef) vocabulary.
    7910                 :            : 
    7911                 :            :     Obviously, we don't want to generate a duplicate ..._TYPE node if
    7912                 :            :     the TYPE_DECL node that we are now processing really represents a
    7913                 :            :     standard built-in type.  */
    7914                 :            : 
    7915                 :            : void

    8751                 :            : 
    8752                 :            : /* Given RICHLOC, a location for a diagnostic describing a missing token
    8753                 :            :    of kind TOKEN_TYPE, potentially add a fix-it hint suggesting the
    8754                 :            :    insertion of the token.
    8755                 :            : 
    8756                 :            :    The location of the attempted fix-it hint depends on TOKEN_TYPE:
    8757                 :            :    it will either be:
    8758                 :            :      (a) immediately after PREV_TOKEN_LOC, or
    8759                 :            : 
    8760                 :            :      (b) immediately before the primary location within RICHLOC (taken to
    8761                 :            :          be that of the token following where the token was expected).
    8762                 :            : 
    8763                 :            :    If we manage to add a fix-it hint, then the location of the
    8764                 :            :    fix-it hint is likely to be more useful as the primary location
    8765                 :            :    of the diagnostic than that of the following token, so we swap
    8766                 :            :    these locations.
    8767                 :            : 
    8768                 :            :    For example, given this bogus code:
